MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: THE STATION IS LOCATED ON THE GRAND TETON; WYTETON CO. 7.5' SERIES (TOPO.) QUADRANGLE. THE DATA ARE ASSOCIATED WITH THE 1998 REPORT "WATER QUALITY IN THE BACKCOUNTRY OF GRAND TETON NATIONAL PARK" PREPARED BY DR. AIDA FARAG AND DANIEL WOODWARD.  THE ORIGINAL DATA SET REPORTED NEGATIVE VALUES FOR AMMONIA; DOC; ORTHOPHOSPHATE; AND TOTAL PHOSPHORUS. MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The hiking trial will lead you right up to the outlet of the lake. Our site is located on the right side of the outlet when you are looking at the lake. The site is at the first sign of running water in the outlet.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Upper Cottonwood Creek near Jenny Lake Ranger Station
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site is between the 2 foot bridges near Jenny Lake Ranger Station.  One bridge leads to the Exum Guides office the other bridge leads to the boat dock.  Site is approximately 100 meters upstream of the Exum Guides bridge.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site is basically in a nondescript area.  Navigating with GPS will be the best method to find this site.  During the site establishment this spot was really the only spot we could safely conduct a discharge measurement and is very close to the site USGS uses previously.  The creek is braided into two distinct channels, which will likely change after next springs high flow.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: At the creek that the flows from Delta Lake follow this to the outlet of the lake. The site is within the boulders of the outlet where you can sample flowing water just at the edge of the lake.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Upper Pacific Creek near USFS Boundary
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: After you cross the USFS/Park boundary take your first right.  There are a bunch of social roads here, stay left and park at the end of this road.  You'll come to a 'campsite' tucked under a bunch of mature spruce trees.  Walk through the site to Pacific Creek.  Wade across a small channel to a gravel bar; the site is about in the middle of the gravel bar, slightly downstream of the campsite.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site is on just upstream (20 feet) from USGS gage on east side of bridge.  Park at bridge and hike down to site.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Pilgrim Creek at Forest Service Boundary
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site is at forest service boundary. Creek is east of parking area about 20 ft. There is a fence running along the road across from parking area. Fence stops at dirt path that leads to creek. Our site is 30 ft below this path. Site is located next to straight away where creek channel comes together briefly before going under log jam.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The site is above Hwy 89 bridge. The 2007 site is between the bridge and the nearest tree in the middle channel of the flood plain. These channels at this site will change season to season, and a new site will need to be located next year.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Jackson Lake is 15 miles long by 3 or 4 miles wide. The Snake River flows into Jackson Lake at its upper end and out again below. The site is located on the northeastern side of the lake.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Pacific Creek about 8 Miles Above Mouth
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The site is located eight miles above the mouth of Pacific Creek.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Unnamed Creek Upper End of Jackson Lake
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The site is located at a small creek that flows into the east side of the upper end of Jackson Lake.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Located about 1/2 mile upstream of the confluence of Sheffield with the Snake River.  About 30 feet upstream of where Teton National Forest Sheffield Creek dirt road meets with Sheffield Creek.  Site is located on the left bank just after the first willows bushes you encounter and above a small tributary that enters the creek.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Sheffield Creek at Confluence with Snake River
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Located 200 feet upstream from the confluence with the Snake River.  The site is just above eroded bend on the stream.  Samples were taken on the left bank on gravel bar.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Snake River at Old Flagg Ranch 1000' Below Bridge
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: North bank of Snake River 180 feet west of power pole.  Located on right bank about 1000 feet downstream of Rte. 89 bridge.  The sampling location is located in the floodplain and is void of brushy or woody vegetation.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Snake River Below Site of New Visitor's Center
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site is located about 500 feet downstream of Moose Bridge/USGS Gage Station.  The site has a homogenous flow just before a gravel island that splits the flow about 600 feet below the site.  The site is on right bank floodplain and on the left bank a secondary high flow channel located runs parallel with the Snake River..

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Spread Creek Forest Service above Dam
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site is above an old dam built in the 40's that is used to divert water to two ditches. The site is located between a small cobble diversion near the dam and a tributary above the site. The site is on the left bank looking down stream. This site spans across two channels. Sampling will be done as a split sample.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site is above Hwy 89 bridge on right side of stream. It is located between to rock gabion below and a small channel coming in above. There is also undercut banks on either side of the site.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: At Surprise Lake follow the trail down to the lake shore. You will see a spur trail going off to the left side of the lake; follow this trail to the outlet. The site is on the right site of the outlet looking at the lake.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: THE STATION IS LOCATED ON THE MOOSE; WYTETON CO. 7.5 MINUTE SERIES (TOPOGRAPHIC) QUADRANGLE.  THE SITE IS LOCATED AT DITCH CREEK WHERE IT CROSSES ANTELOPE FLATS BRIDGE AND IS WITHIN GRAND TETON NATIONAL PARK.  THE DATA ARE FROM THE TETON SCIENCE SCHOOL (JACKSON HOLE; WY). THE SCHOOL TRAINS TEACHERS AND STUDENTS (ELEMENTARY THROUGH HIGH SCHOOL) IN WATER SAMPLING TECHNIQUES.  THE SCHOOL ALSO OFFERS ECOLOGYRELATED CLASSES FOR ALL AGE GROUPS. OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Aster Creek is a small stream that rises in the Red Mountains west of Heart Lake and flows nearly due west.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Crawfish Creek is a tributary to the Lewis River. This stream rises on the Pitchstone Plateau and flows 10 to 15 miles before joining the Lewis River. The site is located on Crawfish Creek below Moose Falls.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Crawfish Creek is a tributary to the Lewis River. This stream rises on the Pitchstone Plateau and flows 10 to 15 miles before joining the Lewis River. The site is located on Crawfish Creek near the trail crossing.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Heron Creek is a small stream which drains a considerable area, lying immediately north of Shoshone Lake. The site is located on Heron Creek near the mouth.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Enos Lake (Inness Lake in the text) is located near Pacific Creek. The lake is about 3 miles long and 1/2 mile wide. The lake is surrounded on most sides by low marshy meadow. Its outlet is into Pacific Creek.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The site is located on the Lewis River near Aster Creek.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The outlet of Shoshone Lake is called Lake Fork or Lewis River. This is a very pretty stream of clear, pure water flowing with a rather rapid current for 3 miles in a direction a little east of south, and then expanding into Lewis Lake. The site is located on the Lewis River near Shoshone Lake.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Pacific Creek about 1 Mile Above Inness (Enos) Lake
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The site is located on Pacific Creek approximately one mile above Enos Lake (Inness Lake in the text).

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Pacific Creek at Two Ocean Pass
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The site is located on Pacific Creek at Two Ocean Pass.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Pacific Creek at Junction with Mink Creek
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The site is located at the junction of Pacific Creek and Mink Creek.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The site is located on a small unnamed branch of Pacific Creek.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The shape of Shoshone Lake is somewhat like a that of the letter T, the upright and crosspieces being each pretty heavy, and the letter being inclined to the right. The portion corresponding to the upright part of the T is constricted at the upper end. The elevation of the lake is 7740 feet. The site is located on the southeast shore of the Shoshone Lake.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The Snake River near 'Presidents Camp' flows through a wide meadow, grassy and open on one side and covered with ha heavy growth of chaparral on the other.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Snake River at Bridge South of Flagg Ranch near USGS Gage
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This water quality site is located approximately 3.2 km outside of Yellowstone National Park south of  the south entrance gate.  The site is mid-way across the bridge that crosses the Snake River near Flagg Ranch and is within the boundaries of John D. Rockefeller Jr. Memorial Parkway.  The watershed upstream of the sample site encompasses approximately 125,873 hectares and drains much of the south-central portion of Yellowstone National Park.
